<span key="a3538b4ae36a4f55babbcdf76fd07a29"><span offset-key="a3538b4ae36a4f55babbcdf76fd07a29:0">Git subtree: the alternative to Git submodule</span></span>

<span key="09db7596e2574263bc4bcb5ec653e244"><span offset-key="09db7596e2574263bc4bcb5ec653e244:0"><span slate-zero-width="n">â€‹</span></span></span>

<span key="83076989acd14b5c8fa08acc3b37c295"><span offset-key="83076989acd14b5c8fa08acc3b37c295:0">The Internet is full of articles on why you shouldnâ€™t use Git submodules. While submodules are useful for a few use cases, they do have several drawbacks.</span></span>

<span key="1d7e71620fcf4d49af0fe7b6ea0a7cfa"><span offset-key="1d7e71620fcf4d49af0fe7b6ea0a7cfa:0">Are there alternatives? The answer is: yes! There are (at least) two tools that can help track the history of software dependencies in your project while allowing you to keep using Git:</span></span>

-   <img src="data:image/svg+xml;base64," class="r-1nf4jbm" />

    <span key="64a1a0cf6d8543ffb273d4811b683119">`git subtree`</span>

-   <img src="data:image/svg+xml;base64," class="r-1nf4jbm" />

    <span key="14e7adc1a5ea4c828e21b36506dcf749"><span offset-key="14e7adc1a5ea4c828e21b36506dcf749:0">Google repo</span></span>

<span key="0dedff367d904749b1a0a774cfad5032"><span offset-key="0dedff367d904749b1a0a774cfad5032:0">In this post we will look at </span>`git subtree `<span offset-key="0dedff367d904749b1a0a774cfad5032:2">and show why it is an improvement â€“ albeit not perfect â€“ over git submodule.</span></span>

## 

<span key="f74d6d3baa1b476ca108b405847fe4f3"><span offset-key="f74d6d3baa1b476ca108b405847fe4f3:0">What is </span>`git subtree`<span offset-key="f74d6d3baa1b476ca108b405847fe4f3:2">, and why should I use it?</span></span>

<span key="fefce533fe884396bd3cb29229af0e5e">`git subtree`<span offset-key="fefce533fe884396bd3cb29229af0e5e:1"> lets you nest one repository inside another as a sub-directory. It is one of several ways Git projects can manage project dependencies.</span></span><span slate-void="true" key="a9eeefd85c87430fb5716a11d409a2ee"></span>

<span key="cefa6fbbe4814c2f9e273bf8e3146da6"><span offset-key="cefa6fbbe4814c2f9e273bf8e3146da6:0"><span slate-zero-width="z">â€‹</span></span></span>

<span key="0966874a343b423c9c1079f0a046d852"><span offset-key="0966874a343b423c9c1079f0a046d852:0">Why you may want to consider </span>`git subtree`</span>

-   <img src="data:image/svg+xml;base64," class="r-1nf4jbm" />

    <span key="fd710a5b17224b038154135cf5d371f0"><span offset-key="fd710a5b17224b038154135cf5d371f0:0">Management of a simple workflow is easy.</span></span>

-   <img src="data:image/svg+xml;base64," class="r-1nf4jbm" />

    <span key="c4ed2a06ce154ceaa1316290c5612b03"><span offset-key="c4ed2a06ce154ceaa1316290c5612b03:0">Older version of Git are supported (even older than v1.5.2).</span></span>

-   <img src="data:image/svg+xml;base64," class="r-1nf4jbm" />

    <span key="790f857fdf1c4d68927bbe2458132c33"><span offset-key="790f857fdf1c4d68927bbe2458132c33:0">The sub-projectâ€™s code is available right after the clone of the super project is done.</span></span>

-   <img src="data:image/svg+xml;base64," class="r-1nf4jbm" />

    <span key="35265f3296454c0a82291ca6184edb8a">`git subtree`<span offset-key="35265f3296454c0a82291ca6184edb8a:1"> does not require users of your repository to learn anything new. They can ignore the fact that you are using </span>`git subtree`<span offset-key="35265f3296454c0a82291ca6184edb8a:3"> to manage dependencies.</span></span>

-   <img src="data:image/svg+xml;base64," class="r-1nf4jbm" />

    <span key="8f55832ee6a54729ac0fb4412e918e93">`git subtree`<span offset-key="8f55832ee6a54729ac0fb4412e918e93:1"> does not add new metadata files like git submodule does (i.e., .gitmodule).</span></span>

-   <img src="data:image/svg+xml;base64," class="r-1nf4jbm" />

    <span key="17e3a548fbe245cbbfe742711c4c1638"><span offset-key="17e3a548fbe245cbbfe742711c4c1638:0">Contents of the module can be modified without having a separate repository copy of the dependency somewhere else.</span></span>

<span key="c7a50704dd83428483306e0857fb4d10"><span offset-key="c7a50704dd83428483306e0857fb4d10:0">Drawbacks (but in our opinion they're largely acceptable):</span></span>

-   <img src="data:image/svg+xml;base64," class="r-1nf4jbm" />

    <span key="0a9d73c6c793462e87354adb1eeca93b"><span offset-key="0a9d73c6c793462e87354adb1eeca93b:0">You must learn about a new merge strategy (i.e.</span>`git subtree`<span offset-key="0a9d73c6c793462e87354adb1eeca93b:2">).</span></span>

-   <img src="data:image/svg+xml;base64," class="r-1nf4jbm" />

    <span key="08e4983926bf435e8faa90c570d185d6"><span offset-key="08e4983926bf435e8faa90c570d185d6:0">Contributing code back upstream for the sub-projects is slightly more complicated.</span></span>

-   <img src="data:image/svg+xml;base64," class="r-1nf4jbm" />

    <span key="1023ead7c41f442091bb35f0214a58dc"><span offset-key="1023ead7c41f442091bb35f0214a58dc:0">The responsibility of not mixing super and sub-project code in commits lies with you.</span></span>

## 

<span key="c16b263be3db43ff9e546ac9bcf05682"><span offset-key="c16b263be3db43ff9e546ac9bcf05682:0">How to use </span>`git subtree`</span>

<span key="ad46ed18f79e47d181d14a0dd4115c9d">`git subtree`<span offset-key="ad46ed18f79e47d181d14a0dd4115c9d:1"> is available in stock version of Git since May 2012 â€“ v1.7.11 and above. ### 

<span key="26adfd90e103417a8a5f8a2c9cc800fd"><span offset-key="26adfd90e103417a8a5f8a2c9cc800fd:0">Can I do this without using the </span>`git subtree`<span offset-key="26adfd90e103417a8a5f8a2c9cc800fd:2"> command?</span></span>
